● Found it. The server handles one request per connection then calls close(fd) — but the response headers never include
  Connection: close. For HTTP/1.1 clients (browsers), the default assumption is keep-alive, so the browser tries to send
   a second range request on the same socket. The server has already closed it with unread data still in the receive
  buffer, which causes the kernel to send TCP RST instead of a graceful FIN. RST discards all buffered data — including
  response data the browser hadn't finished reading — breaking media playback.

  curl works because it makes one request and doesn't attempt connection reuse.

  The fix: add Connection: close to every response from the static handler:

