  Root cause explained: The server processes one request per connection then calls close(fd). When Chrome requests
  audio/video it sends subsequent range requests on the same TCP connection (HTTP/1.1 keep-alive is the default).
  Without Connection: close in the response, Chrome doesn't know the server won't reuse the connection, so it may send
  request #2 before receiving the TCP FIN for request #1. The server closes the socket with that unread data still in
  the receive buffer — Linux kernel sends TCP RST (not FIN). RST causes Chrome to discard all buffered data including
  the in-flight response, breaking playback.

  Fix: Connection: close is now appended to the CORS constant, so every response from handle_static (200, 206, 301, 304,
   4xx) tells the browser to open a fresh connection for each request. curl wasn't affected because it makes one request
   and disconnects.
